31.2 2139 Constructed c. 1790 BC1 Type True pyramid now ruined Height 35 metres 115 ft Base 52 metres 171 ft The pyramid of Ameny Qemau is an ancient Egyptian pyramid located in southern Dahshur. It was constructed for Ameny Qemau a obscure king of the 
13 th Dynasty during the Second Intermediate Period.1 Pyramidedit The stone constituting its upper structure has been entirely robbed but the damaged substructures remain. The pyramid was discovered by Charles Arthur Muss in 1957 and excavated in 1968. The pyramid originally stood 35 metres 115 ft high with a base length of 52 metres 171 ft. The burial chamber comprised from a single colossal block of quartzite similar to that of Amenemhat III with receptacles for the sarcophagus and the canopic jars hewn out of the interior of the block.2 Discovery and excavationsedit The earliest known historical mention of the pyramid of Ameny Qemau is found in the book of the medieval Arab historian Taqi alDin Ahmad AlMaqrizi Geography and History of Egypt3 where AlMaqrizi describes the pyramids of Dashur. The pyramid of Ameny Qemau was rediscovered in 1957 by a team led by Charles Arthur Muss.4 In 1968 Vito Maragioglio and Celeste Rinaldi investigated the architecture of the pyramid.5 More recently the remains of the funerary equipment of the king were published by Nabil Swelim and Aidan Dodson.6 See alsoedit Ancient Egypt portal Egyptian pyramid construction techniques List of Egyptian pyramids Lepsius list of pyramids Referencesedit Wikimedia Commons has media related to Pyramid of Ameni Qemau.  a b K.S.B. Ryholt The Political Situation in Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period c.18001550 BC Carsten Niebuhr Institute Publications vol. 20. Copenhagen Museum Tusculanum Press 1997  Mark Lehner The Complete Pyramids London Thames and Hudson 1997 p.185 ISBN 0500050848.  Taqi alDin Ahmad AlMaqrizi Geography and History of Egypt French translation available online.  Robert Schiestl Pottery from Pyramids of the 
